This is all well and good if you know you have a problem and need to abort, and you have the time to wait for a predetermined velocity to then initiate your escape before things get bad. The people on the challenger did not have that time. It just exploded. Now lets see a test where it explodes or tumbles or other major malfunction BEFORE the initiation of the escape/ejection. That is more realistic of what would (and already has) happened.

This is a lot of celebrating and patting each other on the back for testing a solution to a problem that has never happened.
